d Try my test drive site out to see how it works at http://testdrive.seedprod.com In this post I&#8217;m going to walk you through how to set up a demo site for your plugin or theme that potential customers can use to test out your product. There are a few plugins that exist already [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.seedprod.com/setup-demo-site-plugin-theme/">How to Setup a Demo Site for Your Plugin or Theme</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.seedprod.com">SeedProd</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"John Turner";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12708:"<p><strong>Resources</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/theme.zip">Theme Download</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/plugin.zip">Plugin Download</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Try my test drive site out to see how it works at <a href="http://testdrive.seedprod.com" target="_blank">http://testdrive.seedprod.com</a></p>\n<p>In this post I&#8217;m going to walk you through how to set up a demo site for your plugin or theme that potential customers can use to test out your product. There are a few plugins that exist already but none of them meet my needs so I explored how to create one. Let&#8217;s get started.</p>\n<p>You need a few things to get started. <a href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Create_A_Network" target="_blank">WordPress Multisite</a>, <a href="http://www.gravityforms.com/" target="_blank">Gravity Forms with the User Registration Add On</a> and <a href="https://zapier.com" target="_blank">Zapier</a> (the free version will work).</p>\n<p>Once you have these things in place the next thing you&#8217;ll want to do it activate Gravity Forms on the base site of your multisite instance and create a user registration form. Here&#8217;s what my main demo site looks like. It simply prompts for an email and has a no robot CAPTCHA to prevent spam sign ups and a create button. I want to capture the email so I can follow-up with the potential customer and the rest of the process should be an easy one click and go.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_15-57-08.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-2155" src="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_15-57-08-800x583.jpg" alt="Coming Soon Demo ScreenShot" width="800" height="583" srcset="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_15-57-08-800x583.jpg 800w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_15-57-08-400x292.jpg 400w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_15-57-08-768x560.jpg 768w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_15-57-08.jpg 986w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>\n<p>You can access the theme I use and all other assets at the bottom of the article under Resources at the top of the article.</p>\n<p>To create the Gravity Form for this site make sure you have the User Registration Add On activated on the main WordPress site on your Multisite Install. Then create a new form and add a single line plain text &#8220;username&#8221; field and an email field like this.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_16-11-59.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-2157" src="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_16-11-59-800x685.jpg" alt="2016-04-25_16-11-59" width="800" height="685" srcset="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_16-11-59-800x685.jpg 800w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_16-11-59-400x342.jpg 400w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_16-11-59-768x657.jpg 768w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_16-11-59.jpg 1027w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>\n<p>Then disable any notifications for the form and add a redirect confirmation like this. This will redirect a user back to the main site with the username in the url. We&#8217;ll use this to auto login the user.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_14-30-15.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-2161" src="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_14-30-15-800x500.jpg" alt="2016-04-26_14-30-15" width="800" height="500" srcset="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_14-30-15-800x500.jpg 800w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_14-30-15-400x250.jpg 400w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_14-30-15-768x480.jpg 768w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_14-30-15.jpg 1362w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>\n<p>Next add a User Registration Feed using these settings below. This will create a new site within WordPress multisite for every user who registers on our site. It will also generate a password for them and send them their credentials. You can make check &#8220;User Activation&#8221; depending whether you want the user to verify their email before the site is create or not. Right now I don&#8217;t verify but may in the future if I get lots of fake emails.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_16-14-03.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-2158" src="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_16-14-03-800x1511.jpg" alt="2016-04-25_16-14-03" width="800" height="1511" srcset="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_16-14-03-800x1511.jpg 800w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_16-14-03-400x756.jpg 400w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_16-14-03-768x1451.jpg 768w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-25_16-14-03.jpg 965w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>\n<p>So you&#8217;ll notice we created a form that ask for a username but we don&#8217;t show that field in the registration page. I have added custom code to my theme that hides that field and uses javascript to create the username while they type their email for the form. The code is include in the theme at the top of the article.</p>\n<style>.gist table { margin-bottom: 0; }</style>\n<div class="gist-oembed" data-gist="seedprod/d22ffcdcbfb6bbc5894757e840018839.json"></div>\n<p>Next add the <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/gravity-forms-no-captcha-recaptcha/" target="_blank"><strong>Gravity Forms No CAPTCHA reCAPTCHA </strong></a>plugin from wordpress.org This will allow you to add a better recaptcha than the one provided out of the box with Gravity forms.</p>\n<p>OK, so far we have created a gravity form that creates a site for the user and sends the user his or her info. Remember when created the confirmation that redirected back to the home page with the username. Now we are going to create a small plugin that auto logins our new user and send them to our plugins settings page. If you prefer not to do this and have user confirm their email before they register just make sure to create a default notification instead of redirecting.</p>\n<p>Here&#8217;s the code I use to auto login the user: (This code is include in the plugin at the top of the page.)</p>\n<style>.gist table { margin-bottom: 0; }</style>\n<div class="gist-oembed" data-gist="seedprod/a00d6391d2415d3612140268904e0ddc.json"></div>\n<p>In this code we are exclude our Super Admin username for the multisite from the autologin, accepting  a username and logging in that user to their test site. In the theme we add code to redirect the user to our plugin page if username is passed in. (This code is include in the theme at the top of the page.)</p>\n<style>.gist table { margin-bottom: 0; }</style>\n<div class="gist-oembed" data-gist="seedprod/98f8f25468e4cd53b8e5047489843ca7.json"></div>\n<p>As you can see I added a <em>firstrun=1</em> to the query of the redirect. This allows us to show a video or some kind of on-boarding message on our plugin page.</p>\n<p>Here&#8217;s code I use to show a on-boarding message. In my case I show a message and a video. (This code is include in the plugin at the top of the page.)</p>\n<style>.gist table { margin-bottom: 0; }</style>\n<div class="gist-oembed" data-gist="seedprod/41933ba8d6032727fd734558033b010e.json"></div>\n<p>I also add code to show a contact form. This code show my <a href="https://www.helpscout.net/embed-tools/" target="_blank">HelpScout Beacon</a> contact form. Here&#8217;s the code: (This code is include in the plugin at the top of the page.)</p>\n<style>.gist table { margin-bottom: 0; }</style>\n<div class="gist-oembed" data-gist="seedprod/6a29559ba80ae9fe1a666b7041f7e7d2.json"></div>\n<p>OK the user now has an account and has been on-boarded. They can now test and play with your plugin or theme. The only thing left to do is delete the site after a given amount of time. I give the user 24 hours to test. To delete the site after 24 hours add the <a href="http://www.gravityforms.com/add-ons/zapier/" target="_blank">Gravity Forms Zapier Add On</a> to the main site.</p>\n<p>Log into Zapier and create a new Gravity Forms Zap. Follow the setup instructions provided by Zapier to Connect Gravity Forms to Zapier. Zapier will provide you will a unique url that you will add in Gravity Form that will post the info to Zapier after a form is submitted.</p>\n<p>Next add a Delay by Zapier action. You can set the delay time to fit your needs. In my case I set it to 24hours.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_14-59-18.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-2162" src="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_14-59-18-800x473.jpg" alt="2016-04-26_14-59-18" width="800" height="473" srcset="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_14-59-18-800x473.jpg 800w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_14-59-18-400x236.jpg 400w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_14-59-18-768x454.jpg 768w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_14-59-18.jpg 1378w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>\n<p>Next add GET Webhook action. Enter the url to your demo site and two query string parameters, action and email, with actions value being delete and the email value being value of email from the form.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_15-00-44.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-2163" src="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_15-00-44-800x473.jpg" alt="2016-04-26_15-00-44" width="800" height="473" srcset="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_15-00-44-800x473.jpg 800w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_15-00-44-400x236.jpg 400w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_15-00-44-768x454.jpg 768w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_15-00-44.jpg 1378w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>\n<p>So after 24 hours of the site being created, Zapier will now send a get request with these two parameters. Now all we need to do is delete the site. Here&#8217;s the code I use to listen for the GET request and delete the site.</p>\n<style>.gist table { margin-bottom: 0; }</style>\n<div class="gist-oembed" data-gist="seedprod/10d8cf7453e90768d5fb3ce79a599ce7.json"></div>\n<p>What this code does is exclude any request that passes in our Super Admin email. Then it makes sure we have the action and email and looks up the user id by email. We then find the blogs for that user and delete. Then we delete the user.</p>\n<p>And that&#8217;s it We have create a form that creates a site the we delete it 24 hours later. If you have a pro Zapier account you could add another step  in the zap and add the user to an email marketing sequence. In my case I add the user to my Drip account.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_15-12-23.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-2164" src="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_15-12-23-800x473.jpg" alt="2016-04-26_15-12-23" width="800" height="473" srcset="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_15-12-23-800x473.jpg 800w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_15-12-23-400x236.jpg 400w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_15-12-23-768x454.jpg 768w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-04-26_15-12-23.jpg 1378w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>\n<p>It literally took me 15 minutes to set up my test drive site.  It does every thing I want it to do and I can customize and automate it any way I want. Since I&#8217;m using Zapier I can also send the data anywhere I want. So there you have it, a DIY test drive site for your plugin or theme.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.seedprod.com/setup-demo-site-plugin-theme/">How to Setup a Demo Site for Your Plugin or Theme</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.seedprod.com">SeedProd</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:59:"https://www.seedprod.com/setup-demo-site-plugin-theme/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:46:"Introducing SeedProd Coming Soon Pro Version 5";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:72:"https://www.seedprod.com/introducing-seedprod-coming-soon-pro-version-5/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:81:"https://www.seedprod.com/introducing-seedprod-coming-soon-pro-version-5/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 19 Apr 2016 14:30:50 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Announcements";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:32:"https://www.seedprod.com/?p=2139";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:580:"<p>I&#8217;m proud to announce the latest version of the SeedProd Coming Soon Pro Plugin, Version 5 (Beta). Version 5 has been in development for 9 months and is by far our best release to date! We have been gathering your feedback and have implemented it into some great new features. In Version 5 we are introducing [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.seedprod.com/introducing-seedprod-coming-soon-pro-version-5/">Introducing SeedProd Coming Soon Pro Version 5</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.seedprod.com">SeedProd</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"John Turner";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4554:"<p>I&#8217;m proud to announce the latest version of the SeedProd Coming Soon Pro Plugin, Version 5 (Beta). Version 5 has been in development for 9 months and is by far our best release to date! We have been gathering your feedback and have implemented it into some great new features.</p>\n<p>In Version 5 we are introducing a brand new page builder. No more making changes and then clicking &#8216;Preview&#8217; to see the updated version. Now all your edits, content and design changes will be seen in realtime allowing you to create a Coming Soon or Maintenance Page even faster.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/realtime-page-builder.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-2141" src="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/realtime-page-builder-800x490.jpg" alt="realtime-page-builder" width="800" height="490" srcset="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/realtime-page-builder-800x490.jpg 800w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/realtime-page-builder-400x245.jpg 400w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/realtime-page-builder-768x470.jpg 768w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/realtime-page-builder.jpg 1403w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>\n<p>Also now all our themes are included with every license and over 7000 public domain stock images are available within the builder. Nothing extra to install! Plus we are constantly adding more themes and images.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/coming-soon-page-themes.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-2144" src="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/coming-soon-page-themes-800x459.jpg" alt="coming-soon-page-themes" width="800" height="459" srcset="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/coming-soon-page-themes-800x459.jpg 800w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/coming-soon-page-themes-400x229.jpg 400w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/coming-soon-page-themes-768x440.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>\n<p><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/coming-soon-page-backgrounds.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-2143" src="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/coming-soon-page-backgrounds-800x498.jpg" alt="coming-soon-page-backgrounds" width="800" height="498" srcset="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/coming-soon-page-backgrounds-800x498.jpg 800w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/coming-soon-page-backgrounds-400x249.jpg 400w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/coming-soon-page-backgrounds-768x478.jpg 768w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/coming-soon-page-backgrounds.jpg 1362w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>\n<p>One of the most requested features was the ability to create multiple Coming Soon / Landing Pages per site. Now with the Landing Page add on you can do just that!</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/landing-page-plugin.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-2146" src="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/landing-page-plugin-800x507.jpg" alt="landing-page-plugin" width="800" height="507" srcset="https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/landing-page-plugin-800x507.jpg 800w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/landing-page-plugin-400x253.jpg 400w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/landing-page-plugin-768x486.jpg 768w, https://www.seedprod.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/landing-page-plugin.jpg 1391w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>\n<p>Here&#8217;s a few other notable changes.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Mobile and Desktop Preview</li>\n<li>Code Optimized, virtually zero impact on load times throughout WordPress.</li>\n<li>Uses Flexbox for true Center Alignment</li>\n<li>Realtime Font Changes</li>\n</ul>\n<p>And these features are just the tip of the iceberg.</p>\n<p>We have some exciting new add ons to be released in the next few months that will give the plugin extra functionality beyond coming soon pages.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.seedprod.com/introducing-seedprod-coming-soon-pro-version-5/">Introducing SeedProd Coming Soon Pro Version 5</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.seedprod.com">SeedProd</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:77:"https://www.seedprod.com/introducing-seedprod-coming-soon-pro-version-5/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"1";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:55:"WordPress Maintenance Mode, Everything You Need to Know";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:52:"https://www.seedprod.com/wordpress-maintenance-mode/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:61:"https://www.seedprod.com/wordpress-maintenance-mode/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 28 Jan 2016 16:31:21 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"How To";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:32:"https://www.seedprod.com/?p=2100";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:558:"<p>What is Maintenance Mode? Maintenance Mode is a term you use when you need to take your regular site offline to perform software of content updates. So for example, when WordPress needs to update itself, a plugin or a theme it has a built-in maintenance mode it uses to display a message to visitors that [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.seedprod.com/wordpress-maintenance-mode/">WordPress Maintenance Mode, Everything You Need to Know</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.seedprod.com">SeedProd</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"John Turner";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5765:"<h2>What is Maintenance Mode?</h2>\n<p><strong>Maintenance Mode</strong> is a term you use when you need to take your regular site offline to perform software of content updates. So for example, when WordPress needs to update itself, a plugin or a theme it has a built-in maintenance mode it uses to display a message to visitors that your site is down. Or say you have redesigned your site and you need a few hours to implement the new design. In this case you would use a <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/coming-soon/" target="_blank">maintenance mode plugin</a> to put you site into maintenance mode so you can access the site to make your updates but your visitors would get a custom message about why it&#8217;s down and when it will be back up.</p>\n<p>So essentially WordPress has to versions of a Maintenance Mode.</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>WordPress Built-In</strong> &#8211; to do core, plugins and  themes updates. Note, when WordPress puts itself into Maintenance Mode to perform updates you can not access any part of the site. The front end or the admin back-end. WordPress returns a default message that says: &#8220;<em>Briefly unavailable for scheduled maintenance. Check back in a minute.</em>&#8221; This message can be customized.</li>\n<li><strong>WordPress Maintenance Mode Plugin</strong> &#8211;  to perform updates to your site, but visitors see a custom message.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>When should I a Maintenance Mode Plugin?</h2>\n<p>You should use a Maintenance Mode Plugin when you need to perform updates to your site and you don&#8217;t want your visitors to see the site in an incomplete or transitional state. These plugins should return something called a http 503 status which tell Google and other search engines that the site is down for maintenance and to come back later for indexing. You should not keep your web site  in Maintenance Mode for an extended period of time or it could hurt your SEO. Here&#8217;s more from <a href="https://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com/2011/01/how-to-deal-with-planned-site-downtime.html" target="_blank">Google on how to handle it</a> which most plugins take care of the details as explained in the article.</p>\n<p>One thing you should never to is use a Maintenance Mode plugin when you site is Under Construction or Coming Soon. This will prevent Google From indexing your site.  Here&#8217;s more on the difference <a href="https://www.seedprod.com/coming-soon-vs-maintenance-mode/">between those modes</a>.</p>\n<h2>What Plugin Should I Use?</h2>\n<p>There are many free plugins on <a href="http://wordpress.org" target="_blank">WordPress.org</a> that let you put your website into maintenance mode and display a custom message to your visitors. We recommend our free plugin called. <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/coming-soon/" target="_blank">Coming Soon and Maintenance Mode by SeedProd</a>. This plugin lets you put you site in Coming Soon or Maintenance Mode and handles all the details of returning the correct http status code to Google so you preserve your SEO. If you want to collect emails or have a more customized maintenance page then <a href="https://www.seedprod.com/features/">Check out the Pro Version</a> of the plugin.</p>\n<h2>How to Customize the built-in WordPress Maintenance Mode Message</h2>\n<p>To customize the built-in message which by default says:</p>\n<pre>"<em>Briefly unavailable for scheduled maintenance. Check back in a minute.</em>"</pre>\n<p>You just need to ftp into your WordPress site and upload a file called <strong><em>maintenance.php</em></strong> to your <strong>wp-content</strong> folder. Then whenever WordPress is updating users will see your custom message.</p>\n<h2>How to take a Site out of Maintenance Mode</h2>\n<p>So this seems like a no brainer right. Either WordPress completes its&#8217; updates and it takes itself out of Maintenance Mode or you disable the plugin. Well things do go wrong and it&#8217;s possible for WordPress to get stuck in this mode.</p>\n<h3>How to take WordPress Out of Its&#8217; built in Maintenance Mode</h3>\n<p>So if WordPress gets interrupted while performing a core, plugin or theme update it&#8217;s possible for WordPress to get stuck in Maintenance Mode and you&#8217;ll just see a message that says &#8220;<em>Briefly unavailable for scheduled maintenance. Check back in a minute.</em>&#8221; To manually take WordPress out of its&#8217; built in Maintenance Mode you will need to ftp into your site and remove a hidden file called <strong><em>.maintenance </em></strong>This should then should return your site to the normal state.</p>\n<h3>How to take a WordPress Plugin out of Maintenance Mode</h3>\n<p>If you use a plugin for Maintenance Mode it&#8217;s possible for it to get stuck if you are using a caching plugin or your hosting has a caching layer. In this case you just need to clear the caching plugin&#8217;s cache or clear your host cache. Usually your host will have a button in the WordPress admin that says &#8220;Clear Cache&#8221; If you are unsure contact your host.</p>\n<p>See this video on how to clear WP Super Cache&#8217;s cache:</p>\n<p><iframe class=''youtube-player'' type=''text/html'' width=''640'' height=''390'' src=''https://www.youtube.com/embed/CaIieKPN1LU?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;fs=1&#038;autohide=2&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;wmode=transparent'' allowfullscreen=''true'' style=''border:0;''></iframe></p>\n<p>Hopefully this info was useful and leave a comment if you have any questions.</p>\n<h3></h3>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.seedprod.com/wordpress-maintenance-mode/">WordPress Maintenance Mode, Everything You Need to Know</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.seedprod.com">SeedProd</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36